# ⚠️ MANDATORY: Read Before Starting Frontend Work

**Before you write any frontend code, you MUST:**
1. Read this entire file
2. Run `npm run ci` in `frontend/` to establish baseline (should pass)
3. After your changes, run `npm run ci` again — all checks MUST pass

**Task is NOT done until:** `npm run ci` exits with code 0.

---

# Frontend format, lint, check, tests, and build

- **All checks are mandatory.** Before considering frontend work done, run from `frontend/`:
  - `npm run format` — must pass (Prettier; all files under `src/**/*.{ts,svelte,css,json}` match style).
  - `npm run lint` — must exit with zero and report no errors or warnings (ESLint on `src/`).
  - `npm run check` — must pass (svelte-check with `tsconfig.app.json` and `tsc -p tsconfig.node.json`).
  - `npm run test` — must pass with no failures (Vitest; includes `src/**/*.test.ts`, jsdom, `src/test/setup.ts`).
  - `npm run build` — must succeed (Vite production build).
- **USE THIS:** `npm run ci` is the ONE command that runs format → lint → check → test → build. Run it before starting and after finishing. If it passes, you're done. If it fails, fix and re-run until it passes.
- **BLOCKER: Fix before marking task done.** If ANY check fails, the task is INCOMPLETE. Fix issues (e.g. `npm run lint:fix`, `npm run format:fix`, add or fix tests, fix types) and re-run the full check suite until everything passes. Do not commit or consider the task finished with failing checks.
- **New code must be covered by tests.** When adding or changing code under `frontend/src/`, add or update tests so that the new or changed behavior is covered. Place tests as `*.test.ts` under `src/` (convention: `__tests__/` next to the module, e.g. `src/lib/utils/__tests__/`, `src/lib/components/__tests__/`, `src/lib/api/__tests__/`). Do not leave new logic untested.
- Do not introduce or leave ESLint errors/warnings, Prettier violations, svelte-check/tsc errors, failing tests, or a broken build in the frontend.

- **Common pitfalls that violate this rule:**
  - Running only `npm run test` but not `npm run check` (TypeScript errors hide here)
  - Running tests for only the new file, not the full suite (existing tests may break)
  - Assuming "simple" changes don't need the full gate (they do)
  - Fixing lint/format issues but not re-running tests to verify

